commentText: Today layoffs have nothing to do with AI. Sure LLMs (and the following models) are going to involves layoffs, but in the 10 next years. The number of organisations who are *already* able to replace humans with AI is very very small. Today layoffs are more about a global crisis, with inflation, a US president disturbing the world economy, the invasion of Ukraine, climate warming (just the beginning...), etc. So sure, AI will take jobs, as robots did in factories decades ago, but it just means more time for other activities, at least with the proper political regime (not all for the already most wealthy).

commentText: I want to make one correction to the lady around 9:17. The word you're looking for is "automated tracking system" or ATS. Examples include Workday and Talio. These are not new and as a 32 year old when I graduated when I was younger I encountered them as well (circa 2015-2016). ATS systems have nothing to do with the impact ChatGPT and generative AI has on the labour market and it's not helpful to confuse the two. People have been complaining about ATS systems for a very long time, even before ChatGPT and the like existed. The time when humans would review applications was a very long time ago, like maybe 2010 or thereabouts.

commentText: AI isn't taking jobs, it's AI speculation that's taking jobs. AI has generally underperformed everywhere it's been implemented, with studies generally showing it makes workers less efficient (which the media should know, considering the high-profile embarrassments they've had). As the for the hype, it's largely driven by a mix of speculation, advertising/marketing, and bad assumptions about generative AI's current capabilities. All that said, the reporter(s) and pundit(s) for this story could easily lose their jobs to AI without anything of value being lost because their claims involve as much hallucination and shoddy information as AI.

commentText: The housing collapse was the first crack. Banks gambled, collapsed, and got taxpayer bailouts. Executives handed themselves bonuses with public money while the public paid the price. Occupy Wall Street tried to push back, but nothing truly changed. The same players stayed in power. The rules stayed rigged.  Now we are living through the next phase. Mass layoffs, ghost jobs, AI filters, and stagnant wages are everywhere. Profits soar, shareholders celebrate, and executives cash out while telling workers to be grateful for scraps.  Meritocracy is gone. Optics replaced it. Corporate success is no longer built on value or skill, but on who can perform the best image while cutting the people they parade for PR. Behind the curtain, the human element is gone, and the fa√ßade grows thicker.  AI is not the enemy. The real danger is AI CEOs and executives who treat technology as their personal crown. They are not building; they are competing to out-narcissist each other, blinded by ego and greed. Investors fuel this arms race because it spikes their portfolios, no matter the long-term damage. Behind closed doors, the C-suite and shareholders pat themselves on the back while carving out what remains of the middle class.  This is not about politics. It is about power. The ultra-wealthy control the levers and have no interest in building a system that works for anyone else. This is the second reckoning. The first was the manufacturing carve-out that gutted entire communities. This one is a technological carve-out, and its effects are already eroding the workforce from within.  If you feel invisible, you are not imagining it. This market is not broken; it is built to extract and discard. Until people stop accepting optics for progress and demand substance, the machine will keep grinding through generation after generation.  The ultra-wealthy will not save us. They are too busy competing to see who can burn it down the fastest.

commentText: I drove 45 minutes and showed up to a job interview and told the people at the front desk that I was here for an interview.  They looked confused and asked me for the name of the person I was supposed to be interviewing.  I gave them the name.  A little bit later, that person came out and we went into a private room to start talking.  They told me that the job was "recently filled" and there wasn't anything currently open anymore, but that they liked my resume enough that they wanted to talk to me in-person for "potential future opportunities".  At this point, I was seething so hard, I wanted to yell at them for wasting my time or say something snarky to this hiring manager.  But I practiced self control and played along and did my best as if the job was open, all the while rage was boiling in my stomach;  I didn't want to burn any bridges in-case this company is my last resort down the line and they do have something open in the far future.    But what a waste of my time, my whole day was wasted on this that could have been spent searching/applying for more jobs or preparing for a real interview.

commentText: Why don't many people get a job in Germany? It's simple ‚Äî they don't meet the specific requirements of the companies here. It's not the same as in our home country. While we may be considered highly skilled and reliable workers back home, in Germany, you need to align with the local expectations ‚Äî including soft skills, communication abilities, and especially fluency in German (ideally at the C1 level). German language certificates are not always necessary ‚Äî what really matters is how well you can communicate during the interview. Also, based on my own experience and conversations with HR at my company, there is a common perception that many Indian candidates exaggerate or misrepresent their experience on their CVs, which creates mistrust.  Taking courses at German universities, even short-term Weiterbildung programs, can really help. Don‚Äôt rely solely on your Indian degrees ‚Äî adapting to the local system makes a big difference.  ‚Äî Response from a skilled immigrant working in Germany for 8 years to the indian girl in video (11:10)

I don't think you absolutely need that I believe you will probably get by with a B2 level, but at the least you should have a B1 level.  It is one thing if you fled from another country, then you really have no chance to prepare for this, but if you actively choose a country, no matter which one, you absolutely do have the chance to prepare and you absolutely should!  Personally I believe that speaking the language also will let you have a completely different experience and make life, social interactions and everything so much easier. I would not underestimate the power of language.

commentText:
I'm an engineer from Romania working and living in Germany for more than 8 years now.
 When I came over I did so with a direct contract, though, I did invest time in learning the language at least to a B2 level when I considered looking for a job here. And, while I have 8 years here, my language skills are far from what I want them to be, so I still, periodically, do language courses.
 Since then, with COVID and the drop in German Automotive industry, my company closed but my CEO collected a few of us and started a new one. So, in my 8 years, I collected unemployment for only 1 month.
 Switching out of the Automotive industry (where my main experience was) took about 1.5 - 2 years of constant learning, interviewing and self-correcting.
 I had a lot of interviews where I got to the end stage of the process but it took time, attention to what I could improve after each interview and a significant amount of energy and research. So, work through it, I'm not saying its 100% going to happen, but chances for skilled workers, with German language skills (even poor ones), are quite good in my experience.
 As for German bureaucracy, I come from Romania :) Germany does have more bureaucracy but I find it's functional and quite efficient. The social and taxation systems would probably not work as well without it. However, I do think a lot is over-regulated here and this is consistent with the opinion of my German colleagues :).
 
 What feel is missing and is becoming problematic is digitalization and quality of services. Most, from state provided services (finance, medical, city offices), to private, service oriented, businesses like banks and telecommunication are outdated, overpriced and of mediocre quality.
 
 All in, Germany is, for me, a lot better than Romania, the caveat being: your family and long-time friends are now a long way away. This is not a small factor in your quality of life. There are a lot of things to improve, but this is as much a chance as an issue, since you can be part of improving some aspects and helping your adoptive country.

videoTitle: The Brutal Reality of the Tech Job Market
videoDescription: The tech job market right now is brutal. Layoffs, endless applications, and constant rejections. It feels impossible to land an offer.
commentText: I've come to the conclusion that I no longer want to chase after a language or framework. This changes all the time. I've also decided that I will no longer subject myself to being treated like a commodity at a cattle auction. In the end, all of this is designed to make you accept doing more for less. I think at some point we give in and accept unrealistic things because the "market demands it," or the influencer you follow or the group of followers in the bubble you're in dictates that this is the culture, technology, or method to be adopted. Yes, I went through a financial setback and had to accept working in other segments. But that didn't kill my desire to work with software. Today, I think the path is to work as an entrepreneur and consultant for small businesses, creating solutions for the region you live in or where you can work without creating a burden on your life. Another mistake I see is the industrialization of the IT workforce. We didn't start that way; we started in a garage or on a small project; we're not cattle.

commentText: Very interesting to learn about the experiences of an expat in Germany. I am a German and lived in the USA for 12 years, but did not work there and my husband is American. Still....the experience is similar. You always experience a culture shock, even when you come from a similar one. Anyway...to fully enjoy the new culture you have to learn everything about it and you have to adjust. The new culture will not adjust to you. Learning the native language is the most important thing. Germans expect you to speak German, in France they expect you to speak French etc. At work you might get away with English, but when you want your electricity to be cut on or whatever you need to speak the native language of the country you live in. Just because English is the widely spread language you cannot expect that everybody can speak two languages. In the US nobody would expect that amybody knows the Italian or German language. About the handshake....Take my word for it...when you grow up with it, it is a normal thing and the way we say hello. And yes, when you shake anybody's hand you look in the eyes of that person. Anything else would not make any sense. And I agree...before anybody moves to another country they should learn about the culture beforehand. What you do inside your home is up to you, but when you step outside please show respect to the country you live in. When my girlfriend came for a visit to the USA she wanted to sunbath top less at the community pool. It took me a long time to convince her that she cannot to this in the USA. To her it was so normal that she could not get her head wrapped around it that she could end up in jail in the US for doing so. It is really important to know about the culture if you plan to live there. It also helps to talk to natives and show interest. They love to learn about your culture also.

commentText: A great honest take on business life in Germany. I compare and contrast this to people who have spend the same amount of time in USA or Australia and feel more at home there. The other major point of assimilation is how we have been open to the culture and relationships in the adopted Country. Did we marry there, did we raise our kids to think like a local or think like an Indian, do you enjoy and partake in local sports, or stick to only cricket. Do you volunteer your time for the good of local people or work for agencies that help out locals? How have you inserted yourself into becoming one with your neighborhood town/city? These things make a huge difference in the way you assimilate into a new culture OR you can remain an expat and take your wealth and go back to India in retirement.  Good thought provoking video!

commentText: The guy is definitely very knowledgeable about Germany but there is a point i would like to make:  Yes house prices have risen dramatically in the decade  until 2023. Since then prices are stagnant.  Now that decade was an exception caused by extraordinarily low interest rates that effectively induced a real estate bubble.  The next decade is very unlikely to see the same growth in prices, so basically up to 2023 it was really hard to lose money with real estate. In the years to come it will be hard to make money with real estate, obviously not impossible but real hard.

commentText: Very insightful. Great video. I lived my whole life in Germany and still don't feel home there. That's why we moved to Istanbul. I just don't agree with one point in the interview. Doubling of your property investment in 10 years. I think there was a very special time window in the last 10 years in Germany (but also many other countries). Back then property prices were relatively low since interest rates were high. But then property rose quite a lot and today they are "relatively" high. Given the economic prospect of Germany, I wouldnt bet property prices will double in the next ten years.

commentText: There is no such thing as a dream job unless you are self employed in your home town with good income, surrounded by your grannies and nannies and eating home food every day sitting on the lap of your mother! Every job is a challenge and a compromise and the further you get out from your comfort home or country the more challenging it gets. That is where Indian youths who have been pampered at home fail abroad with social adjustment in a new society. They are home sick all the time. They should be concentrating on learning new language, new culture, new skills, seeing new places, experiencing the diversity and nature and even enjoying the quietness and lonliness filled with personal advancement. Glad that you pointed out many of these things here. Europe or any where else is definitely not a bed of roses. Nobody is waiting for you with open arms to give you a job, a home or a car. It is a healthy struggle here all the way minus nepotism, corruption, unequality and injustice which you are hopefully trying to get away from.

commentText: For inexperienced workers, I think another huge factor is the increasingly short-term way companies are run. It simply doesn't make sense to hire and train junior people when your company outlook is measured in quarters rather than decades, because they represent high risk of failure on critical short-term deadlines, compounded by high indirect cost to the productivity of the senior people that train them and could otherwise be focussed fully on critical tasks, both of which are naturally compounded by AI as an alternative, but existed well before it.  Add the pattern of company hopping that's more and more popular, which effectively means that training new people is paying for their next employer's benefit more than your own, and it's not hard to see why companies just don't want to deal with entry level people any more.  Of course, that's unsustainable in the long run, but for that, see both of the above: in a business where your incentives are quarterly and *you* expect to jump after a few years too, the long run is some future employee's problem, not yours.  Eventually I think we'll end up needing policy incentives for what I think of as "sustainable hiring" where there are subsidies or similar cost offsetting measures in place to encourage the creation of early career positions and training, because as senior people leave the workforce into retirement, there won't be enough young people gaining the experience to replace them, and that's not something companies are likely to fix for themselves in the current environment.

Not that we'd know what the current rate of Unemployment is right now since we haven't gotten Jobs or GDP reports since October.

commentText: The unemployment in Germany has risen to roughly 2,8 mio. people, yet that is still historically a quite low level. 1,6 mio. of these people have no degree / apprenticeship at all and 50% of unemployed have no German citizenship and might struggle with language, culture and education. Of the remaining 1,2 mio. people with degrees a third is 55+ with difficulties in acquiring new skills and a substantial number (I guess around 200k additionally) lives in so called lost regions of former industries both in the east and west. If you look at these numbers for Germany, the problem seems to be hiring freezes as the only ones that still hire are the state / government or any adjacent jobs to them. It doesn't look as bleak mid-term (roughly 400k more people retire from the workforce than young people entering it per year), yet that doesn't help in the short-term.   It is such a paradox situation, there is a lack of skilled workers and no one wants to hire the ones that are there due to the economic uncertainty and economic cooldown. Companies try to 'sit-it-out' till it gets better, a lot of my friends are overworked as companies put on more pressure instead of hiring new people. AI doesn't affect their jobs directly.   Guess everyone needs to skill up the next months to either prepare for a post-AI world (there will be jobs, yet the skills required are different) or go for another direction altogether (quite some people take double degrees now). The crazy thing is that multiple things happen all at once making it more difficult to find the right personal response to it.

commentText: >Unemployment is close to the historical average Using unemployment isn't entirely accurate, as you have to be actively looking for work to be unemployed; US 2014-2016 data are technically around average as Obama's "unemployment below 8%" claims, but a large part of that is a lot of unemployed workers stopped looking for work, and 2020-2023 caused a lot of people to retire early or just die because of COVID, so they don't technically count as unemployed and dead people don't count in labor force participation either. Underemployment due to people taking gig jobs or lower paying jobs can also misrepresent employment. Also, H-1B immigration necessarily requires having a job, so mass importing employed people from other countries during the Biden years will dilute the apparent unemployment rate among natives. It's a very imperfect metric.

commentText: It's not AI, it's low hiring/low firing economy, especially in the US. Companies are hoarding workers and not firing anyone, which keeps the unemployment rate low, but they're also not hiring any new people, which makes it hard to find a job. It's symptom of the weird permanently pre-recession economy the US is in where the economy is always on the brink of a recession but never goes under all the while headline numbers stay strong. Which is mostly a consequence of K shaped economy where headline numbers like GDP growth and consumption are propped up by the top 10% richest Americans who keep spending while everyone else cuts back.

commentText: 1:51 and 2:43‚Äî the official unemployment rate is almost constant in the US/UK/Germany, except COVID period. There's like 1.5x or less variation, that cannot be called "must harder to find a job". And the rest of the video is trying to explain why unemployment rate is rising (insignificantly), while in the beginning we saw that it's not rising (almost).  My one hypothesis for now is that while unemployment rate is constant, it may be still harder to change a job ‚Äî it may be less people taking more time to find a new job, so the total number time√ópeople is approximately constant. In case of IT it could be, for example, that companies consider much more candidates before choosing one due to some cultural shift after COVID, and that causes candidates to send much more resumes and spend much more time to find a new job (I mean AI resume filtering stage + more interviews for more candidates before hiring + more remote jobs to choose from a larger candidate pool). That's an assumption, I don't have hard data for this except for long term unemployment that grows faster than simple unemployment since early 2023. My second hypothesis is that the official unemployment statistics may not reflect the real unemployment for some reason.

commentText: As a Recruiter who was working with Big Tech until April this year, I can tell you that a lot of times companies close the jobs from their end on the Applicant tracking systems. But jobs continue to show because 1] there is a sync error/lag between the system and the various job portals integrated with it. So jobs remain published on portals even though the company is no longer accepting applications. 2] Several job portals/aggregators keep reposting old/expired job ads to attract candidates and expand their databases. They lure candidates with free to create accounts. Then, they sell this database to company recruiters. Bigger the database, higher the price. They don't care whether jobs shown are legit. As an aggregator, their liability is limited.

commentText: When of the biggest challenges is staying current with your skills. Software and platforms are undergoing generational changes every year. If you are out of the market for 6 months, there may  no longer be a need for your skill set. You couldn't even qualify for the job you left as they are using newer or at least upgraded platforms.  This is extremely stressful and frustrating to someone who is just trying to get a toe hold in the market and stay there. One thing not talked about much is that so much of this work is now done through contractors and vendors. You get a 6 month contract, you're nearing the end of it so you start looking for your next gig. Recuiters don't need you in 3 weeks at the end of your contract. They need you today. That job posting wont even be there when your contract ends. This virtually guarantees periods of unemployment.

videoTitle: Will The Tech Job Market Ever Recover?
videoDescription: Mass layoffs, automation, and deceptive hiring practices have left hundreds of thousands of tech workers unemployed. Fake job ...
commentText: Current Challenges in the Tech Job Market Massive Layoffs: Over 260,000 tech jobs were cut globally in 2023, followed by 150,000+ in 2024 and 25,000+ in 2025.  Automation Impact: Nearly 50% of executives report increased automation, replacing mid-level engineering and administrative roles.  Fake Job Listings: 55% of tech companies post fake job ads, with 70% of recruiters considering it acceptable.  Low Interview Rates: Only 8% of tech job applicants receive interview responses, down from 12% in previous years.  Corporate Ghosting: Many applicants receive no response even after multiple interview rounds.  Longer Job Searches: The average time to secure a tech job in the U.S. has risen from 3 to 5+ months.  Mental Health Strain: Endless rejections and ghosting have led to widespread frustration among job seekers.  Decline in Entry-Level Roles: Entry-level tech job postings dropped by 30% in the UK and over 70% for software developers in the U.S. (2023-2025).  Rising Unemployment: IT sector unemployment reached 5.5% in May 2025, surpassing the national average.  Shifts in Hiring and Job Demand AI-Driven Job Growth: AI-related roles (machine learning, data science, cloud computing) are growing despite declines in traditional tech jobs.  Changing Skill Requirements: Companies now prioritize practical certifications over traditional degrees.  Fewer General IT Jobs: Tech support and generic software engineering roles are shrinking.  New Job Creation: AI is generating demand for specialized roles (AI scientists, cybersecurity experts, data architects).  Struggles for New Graduates: Unemployment for recent graduates is at 7%, the highest in a decade, with 30-40% fewer entry-level openings.  Visa Challenges: Over 10,000 H1B visa holders lost jobs in 2023, with many struggling to find new placements.  Future Projections & Recovery Selective Recovery: The job market is rebounding slowly but unevenly, favoring niche AI and automation-related roles.  18% Growth in Tech Jobs: The U.S. Department of Labor predicts 350,000+ new tech jobs annually by 2034, mostly in AI and cybersecurity.  No Return to Pre-2022 Levels: The market won‚Äôt regain its 2021-2022 hiring peaks; instead, it will become more specialized.  Permanent Structural Changes: Mass hiring and extravagant perks are fading as companies prioritize efficiency and automation.  Adaptation Required: Job seekers must upskill in AI, cloud computing, and cybersecurity to remain competitive.

commentText: Everyone who is saying usa is not easiest to get into and has discrimination should know some things. As someone who has done extensive research on this topic and actually made contact with people who are doing their post graduation in these countries. What he is saying is the absolute truth USA is the easiest to get into for medical pg. Even in australia you won't get any specialisation of your choice even if you clear both amc exams , the specialities you get are only the seats leftover after all Aussie graduates are taken (doctors are less in australia but so are colleges that produce them)  - and there are few specialities like emergency medicine left for imgs. As of UK plab isn't ur license to specialisation in the uk it is just an exam you pass to work in UK after clearing plab you still have to pass mrcp / mrcog / mrcs .etc which 70% people who are doctors in the UK fail to pass. Not to mention the job scarcity even after clearing plab 1 and plab 2 due to inflation. The salary in nhs is barely liveable in uk , laymen get paid more than doctors in uk. So yes usa has the least discrimination against foreign doctors and the only hurdle is usmle atleast they guarantee a job in specialities like internal medicine , family medicine and emergency medicine if you perform well in usmle and play your cards right from the start.

commentText: The likelihood of coming to Germany as a student and securing a job afterward is quite limited because Germany generally encourages students to immigrate temporarily and then return to their home countries after graduation. Unlike the US, UK, and other countries where students often stay and work permanently, this is not typically the case in Germany. While it's possible to find lower-level jobs that don't match your qualifications simply because you're fluent in German, this isn't a sustainable long-term strategy. High taxes and living costs mean that you probably won't become wealthy; instead, you'll live an average life. Additionally, there's intense competition, and employers tend to favor native Germans over migrants.   German employers also usually prefer candidates from prestigious US and British universities like Yale or Cambridge over student immigrants with a university degree from Germany. This is a fact. They often welcome international students primarily for economic reasons, not necessarily to provide more employment opportunities. I know an American who studied here,  became fluent in German (C1 level), speaking almost like a native, but she told me most employers rejected her in favor of native Germans. She eventually returned to the US.   So, believing that studying in Germany will guarantee a job afterward is an illusion. There are already highly qualified refugees from other countries who are unemployed here. Many YouTube channels don't have a thorough understanding of the German system; while some are relatively trustworthy, they still lack complete knowledge and experience. Comparatively, this YouTube is genuine, although the guy didn't cover some other facts, which I can understand may be due to a lack of knowledge of the German system.

commentText: I'm 67, and I'm still working as an estimator for a mid-size sheetmetal fabricator in the central plains Midwest. Been at it for 2 years, and it's my swan song job hopefully until 73 when I'm going to end it (provided I'm still above ground, ambulatory, and don't die on the hill of at will employment). Japanese lean manufacturing model, clean new plant, treated fairly, paid fairly, paid every Friday. Can't ask for much more. Prior to this all my other employers acted like street hoods, and managed their businesses like correctional facilities. I remember with the many recessions I've lived through, this "manufacturing jobs" can take a hike, and those displaced workers along with it. But now it's the tech workers, government workers...... being bent over, and the talking heads spin is demanding some type of equity and action to be taken.  It's easier to find an astronaut than someone who can powder coat metal parts and assemblies, or someone willing to earn while you learn OJT (same for welding, machinist work.......). I see it, our competitors see it, our customers see it, our suppliers see it. But what we're not seeing are the displaced (and long-term unemployed tech workers) sucking it in, and applying for said jobs. Yeah, you don't earn doctor's wages (then go to medical school I guess), and you don't get to do the "day in the life of a young female tech worker" videos.  This isn't the be all to end all, but honest work is honest, and I can say unequivocally (having lived this) that long-term unemployment is shaking one's death rattle.

commentText: I am a Lithuanian national living between Lithuania and Germany. I firmly believe that Germany will recover and regain its strength. Often, we point fingers at Germany because it is a significant global player, but we forget that many other countries have been struggling for the past four years.  I also think there‚Äôs a cultural aspect to this criticism. People sometimes dislike Germany because Germans are perceived as conservative and expect foreigners to adapt to and respect their culture and language. However, those who move to Germany benefit immensely from the opportunities it offers. That said, success requires effort and commitment. Personally, I have never experienced hate or discrimination. Ignorant people exist everywhere, but that doesn‚Äôt define an entire country.  I don‚Äôt wish for Germany‚Äôs downfall, on the contrary, I believe the country is home to many remarkable people who are patriotic and want Germany to succeed. Recent challenges have served as a wake up call not only for Germany but for Europe as a whole. I am confident that Germans and Europeans will take steps to implement new laws and policies to strengthen their economies, military, and collaboration going forward.  Is it worth coming to Germany-yes, if you are willing to put in work! There are a lot of doors that Germany can open if you are willing to work hard enough! And if people will work hard enough and live through tough times, Germany will regain the growth of the economy in no time!

commentText: I agree with all that you said, but as a foreigner in Germany, who got a bachelor degree here and has work experience as well, I think, there is one more thing you should take into consideration.   You may speak German very well and have work experience as well as good notes from your studies, but an employer can still prefer a person, who grew up in Germany over you. If you stay in your home country, you'll have easier time finding a job  just because of that. I'm talking about racism. Racism exists everywhere, but right now in Germany because of the job market situation and because of the current rise of far-right politics, you are more likely to experience racism in the job seaking process. Especially when you are from one of the stigmatized countries like Syria, Iraq, Russia, Turkey und so on.
